1
00:00:06,757 --> 00:00:08,675
<i>Pat o'brien: The picture
you're about to</i> see

2
00:00:08,675 --> 00:00:11,135
<i>is dedicated as
a loving tribute</i>

3
00:00:11,136 --> 00:00:13,138
<i>to that special breed
of human being who,</i>

4
00:00:13,138 --> 00:00:16,141
<i>from the beginning, has been
the backbone and wonder</i>

5
00:00:16,141 --> 00:00:19,352
<i>of that spirit that was
to become the American dream.</i>

6
00:00:21,647 --> 00:00:23,815
<i>The individual who would
stand up and fight</i>

7
00:00:23,815 --> 00:00:26,150
for what
he believes is right,

8
00:00:26,151 --> 00:00:28,319
<i>no matter how overwhelming
the odds.</i>

9
00:00:41,667 --> 00:00:45,170
<i>The story takes place
in our nation's capital,</i>

10
00:00:45,170 --> 00:00:47,297
<i>when certain isolated groups
of people</i>

11
00:00:47,297 --> 00:00:49,632
<i>were beginning to ask
for a freeze on the building</i>

12
00:00:49,633 --> 00:00:52,260
<i>of nuclear plants,
and the stockpiling</i>

13
00:00:52,261 --> 00:00:54,221
<i>of nuclear weapons.</i>

14
00:00:55,722 --> 00:00:59,016
<i>About six months before
our story begins,</i>

15
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:01,644
<i>congress had appointed a
committee under the chairmanship</i>

16
00:01:01,645 --> 00:01:03,855
<i>of senator Sam foley...</i>

17
00:01:03,855 --> 00:01:07,108
<i>To investigate the allegations
of these groups,</i>

18
00:01:07,109 --> 00:01:09,236
<i>that through campaign
contributions</i>

19
00:01:09,236 --> 00:01:12,364
<i>and lucrative construction
contracts,</i>

20
00:01:12,364 --> 00:01:15,075
<i>the nuclear industry had
actually gained control</i>

21
00:01:15,075 --> 00:01:17,702
<i>over the nuclear regulatory
commission,</i>

22
00:01:17,703 --> 00:01:21,123
<i>and the governmental agencies
that were supposed to police it.</i>

23
00:01:22,541 --> 00:01:25,710
<i>As our picture opens,
senator foley,</i>

24
00:01:25,711 --> 00:01:27,587
<i>after months
of closed sessions,</i>

25
00:01:27,588 --> 00:01:31,425
<i>without warning,
abruptly cancels the hearing,</i>

26
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:34,386
<i>and, in an unusual move,</i>

27
00:01:34,386 --> 00:01:37,305
<i>mysteriously seals
all the information</i>

28
00:01:37,306 --> 00:01:39,850
<i>uncovered during
the investigation</i>

29
00:01:39,850 --> 00:01:43,019
<i>as "classified top secret."</i>

30
00:01:43,020 --> 00:01:45,981
<i>And then quietly
gives the green light</i>

31
00:01:45,981 --> 00:01:49,359
<i>for the continued development
of nuclear plants</i>

32
00:01:49,359 --> 00:01:51,819
<i>and nuclear weapons.</i>

33
00:01:51,820 --> 00:01:54,948
Well, i-- I'll take your
questions one at a time,

34
00:01:54,948 --> 00:01:56,908
- to make it manageable.
- Senator, I've been hearing

35
00:01:56,908 --> 00:01:58,576
that you didn't actually
want these hearings cancelled.

36
00:01:58,577 --> 00:02:00,161
Is there someone who's been
ordering these

37
00:02:00,162 --> 00:02:00,996
hearings canceled?

38
00:02:00,996 --> 00:02:04,416
You know better that that, Joe.

39
00:02:04,416 --> 00:02:07,335
With so many deaths that
have been reported, the public--

40
00:02:07,336 --> 00:02:08,003
that's true.

41
00:02:08,003 --> 00:02:09,087
...beginning to suspect
a cover-up.

42
00:02:09,087 --> 00:02:11,380
Senator, if your committee,
which is supposed to police

43
00:02:11,381 --> 00:02:14,759
nuclear safety, is cancelled,
who gonna do the policing?

44
00:02:14,760 --> 00:02:17,179
L-- my announcement stands.

45
00:02:17,179 --> 00:02:20,473
Now, I see no point
in any further responses.

46
00:02:27,939 --> 00:02:29,565
No more questions.

47
00:02:29,566 --> 00:02:31,442
Is something wrong, sir?

48
00:02:31,443 --> 00:02:32,735
He's sick.

49
00:02:32,736 --> 00:02:35,947
- Get a doctor here!
- Please, clear the aisles.

50
00:02:35,947 --> 00:02:37,740
I'm gonna call a doctor.

51
00:02:41,995 --> 00:02:44,747
Give me
the urgent desk, please.

52
00:02:48,168 --> 00:02:51,754
- Pardon me. Pardon me.
- Are you senator foley's aide?

53
00:02:51,755 --> 00:02:52,672
She is.

54
00:02:52,673 --> 00:02:54,925
Okay. Here's his briefcase
and all his papers.

55
00:02:54,925 --> 00:02:57,677
- Oh. I'll give 'em to her.
- Okay, thank you.

56
00:02:59,596 --> 00:03:02,181
- I'm gonna go call his wife.
- Okay, honey. Be right there.

57
00:03:05,811 --> 00:03:09,356
- Oh, I'm terribly sorry.
- I'll get it. That's all right.

58
00:03:09,356 --> 00:03:11,358
- I'm really sorry.
- I know that.

59
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:12,942
Bye-bye.

60
00:06:50,201 --> 00:06:52,494
Yes, operator. I want to make
a person-to-person call

61
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:55,915
to governor Hubert hopper,
and bill it to my office number.

62
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:57,709
This is senator Joseph Payne.

63
00:07:00,337 --> 00:07:03,506
Hello.

64
00:07:03,506 --> 00:07:04,757
You're kidding.

65
00:07:04,758 --> 00:07:07,093
I know it couldn't have come
at a worse time.

66
00:07:07,093 --> 00:07:09,637
Call Bailey, tell him
I'm taking the next flight home.

67
00:07:09,638 --> 00:07:11,181
What is it, Hubert?

68
00:07:11,181 --> 00:07:15,185
Sam foley died.

69
00:07:17,896 --> 00:07:20,523
Thank you.

70
00:07:20,523 --> 00:07:22,483
I don't even
understand the question.

71
00:07:22,484 --> 00:07:23,693
Just go back and tell them--

72
00:07:23,693 --> 00:07:25,194
I don't even know what
they want from me anymore.

73
00:07:25,195 --> 00:07:29,365
Do you have foley's nuclear
file? That's all I'm asking.

74
00:07:32,661 --> 00:07:35,080
I tell you on Saturday
they come after you.

75
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:36,331
Try to take an afternoon off,

76
00:07:36,331 --> 00:07:38,041
can't even play
a game of tennis.

77
00:07:38,041 --> 00:07:40,168
What was that all about?

78
00:07:40,168 --> 00:07:44,668
Well, some clown from the
justice department.

79
00:07:44,714 --> 00:07:47,091
He's asking me if I've
got any of that material

80
00:07:47,092 --> 00:07:49,844
that foley's committee had
on the nuclear contracts.

81
00:07:49,844 --> 00:07:51,512
- Do you?
<i>'</i> No!

82
00:07:51,513 --> 00:07:53,223
I don't know what ever
happened to any of that stuff.

83
00:07:53,223 --> 00:07:55,391
I do.

84
00:07:55,392 --> 00:07:57,185
What?

85
00:07:57,185 --> 00:08:00,104
I have it.

86
00:08:00,105 --> 00:08:03,274
What?

87
00:08:03,274 --> 00:08:07,027
That, honey, is our ticket up.

88
00:08:07,028 --> 00:08:09,822
Dan, are you crazy?

89
00:08:10,907 --> 00:08:12,074
Come on, we need a fourth.

90
00:08:12,075 --> 00:08:13,367
Great idea!

91
00:08:13,368 --> 00:08:15,536
Come on,
it's only your husband.

92
00:08:15,537 --> 00:08:16,955
You've been here all day.

93
00:08:16,955 --> 00:08:18,039
- Come on.
- Please.

94
00:08:18,039 --> 00:08:19,373
Let's go.
Come on, you need it.

95
00:08:19,374 --> 00:08:20,500
Come on, come on, come on.

96
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:21,459
I'm coming.
I'm up, I'm up.

97
00:08:21,459 --> 00:08:22,710
Don't forget your racquet.

98
00:08:22,711 --> 00:08:25,088
Hey, I'll tell you
about it later, ok?

99
00:08:25,088 --> 00:08:27,298
I love you.

100
00:08:36,224 --> 00:08:37,683
Mcghan, go in there
and tell Bailey

101
00:08:37,684 --> 00:08:39,352
that I've got to
give them an answer.

102
00:08:39,352 --> 00:08:40,603
Why don't you tell him, hubie?

103
00:08:40,603 --> 00:08:42,354
I mean after all,
it's your office.

104
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:45,274
All right,

105
00:08:45,275 --> 00:08:48,528
all right, I will.

106
00:08:50,947 --> 00:08:55,447
My concern is with this willet
creek nuclear plant on the fire.

107
00:08:56,453 --> 00:08:58,705
Well, what's wrong with it?
It's ready to roll, isn't it?

108
00:08:58,705 --> 00:09:00,123
Oh, yeah,
it's attached as a rider

109
00:09:00,123 --> 00:09:01,624
where no one will notice it.

110
00:09:01,624 --> 00:09:02,916
Then what are you
worried about?

111
00:09:02,917 --> 00:09:04,585
Nothing, unless the man
we appoint as senator

112
00:09:04,586 --> 00:09:06,963
begins to ask questions.

113
00:09:06,963 --> 00:09:09,715
I mean, unless you're
absolutely sure of him.

114
00:09:09,716 --> 00:09:11,551
It might be better
to postpone the nuclear plant

115
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:14,136
until the next session
of congress.

116
00:09:14,137 --> 00:09:16,389
No, Joe, it's just not
possible to postpone.

117
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,724
Now we'll just have to appoint
somebody we can trust.

118
00:09:18,725 --> 00:09:21,811
Now, wait a minute,
someone we can trust?

119
00:09:21,811 --> 00:09:23,312
Well, who did you think
we'd appoint,

120
00:09:23,313 --> 00:09:24,897
the chairperson
of a feminist league?

121
00:09:25,982 --> 00:09:27,400
Well, there you go again, Jim.

122
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:30,152
Is that all you're ever
concerned about is Washington?

123
00:09:30,153 --> 00:09:31,821
Don't you guys ever
think about my problems

124
00:09:31,821 --> 00:09:32,988
down here in the state?

125
00:09:32,989 --> 00:09:34,573
You're panicking, Hubert!

126
00:09:34,574 --> 00:09:36,450
In my judgment,
the simplest thing to do

127
00:09:36,451 --> 00:09:38,494
is to slip this thing through
just the way it's going

128
00:09:38,495 --> 00:09:40,663
and get it over with,
don't you agree Joe?

129
00:09:40,663 --> 00:09:42,581
Absolutely.
But we have to be sure

130
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:44,333
the man we pick will go along.

131
00:09:44,334 --> 00:09:45,918
Judge Miller.

132
00:09:45,919 --> 00:09:48,922
Miller? Oh, for god's sakes,
come on, will ya?

133
00:09:48,922 --> 00:09:51,257
Horace Miller.
It's a good idea.

134
00:09:51,257 --> 00:09:53,926
I mean, he was a reliable guy
before we put him on the bench,

135
00:09:53,927 --> 00:09:55,678
he's a reliable guy
now that he's on the bench.

136
00:09:55,678 --> 00:09:56,929
Now, what have you got
against him, hubie?

137
00:09:56,930 --> 00:09:58,765
I mean he's exactly
what you want.

138
00:09:58,765 --> 00:10:02,143
He's got class, dignity, he's
always kept his skirts clean.

139
00:10:02,143 --> 00:10:04,103
You forgot one
little thing Jim.

140
00:10:04,104 --> 00:10:08,604
Those people out there won't
stand for it, not for a minute!

141
00:10:10,610 --> 00:10:15,110
We've given you your man.
Just make the announcement.

142
00:10:16,699 --> 00:10:19,535
I won't do it.

143
00:10:19,536 --> 00:10:22,038
Look, I can't just go out there
and give them an ultimatum.

144
00:10:22,038 --> 00:10:24,665
I've got to make them feel
like they have a voice!

145
00:10:28,044 --> 00:10:29,962
How about if we work for some
Harmony here, gentlemen, huh?

146
00:10:29,963 --> 00:10:34,463
What do you say?
A little Harmony?

147
00:10:34,467 --> 00:10:38,345
Horace Miller.

148
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:48,439
Billy Jack?

149
00:10:48,439 --> 00:10:50,524
A half-breed Indian nut?

150
00:10:50,525 --> 00:10:52,860
An ex-convict.
He's not even eligible.

151
00:10:52,861 --> 00:10:55,238
He is now. I've already
granted him a full pardon,

152
00:10:55,238 --> 00:10:57,531
restored all of his rights,
enabling him to be appointed.

153
00:10:57,532 --> 00:11:02,032
And you have also
buried yourself, Hubert!

154
00:11:02,245 --> 00:11:04,622
Governor, that's the most
stupid political stunt

155
00:11:04,622 --> 00:11:06,874
anyone's ever tried
to pull on Bailey.

156
00:11:08,918 --> 00:11:12,504
Jim! Jim, you want
to hear me out?

157
00:11:17,760 --> 00:11:20,596
Jim, listen to me
for a minute!

158
00:11:20,597 --> 00:11:22,765
Look, Jim, it's only
for two short months.

159
00:11:22,765 --> 00:11:24,433
Now, even if he takes
the appointment,

160
00:11:24,434 --> 00:11:25,810
he'd never run
for re-election,

161
00:11:25,810 --> 00:11:27,603
and he'd never make it
if he did run.

162
00:11:27,604 --> 00:11:30,064
The man is so disinterested
in everything political,

163
00:11:30,064 --> 00:11:32,483
he probably wouldn't even
show up in the senate.

164
00:11:32,483 --> 00:11:34,610
And look, by appointing him,

165
00:11:34,611 --> 00:11:36,321
overnight our party
gets a whole new image.

166
00:11:36,321 --> 00:11:38,948
You know, we get the human
righters, the environmentalists,

167
00:11:38,948 --> 00:11:40,699
the Indians, the blacks,
the chicanos,

168
00:11:40,700 --> 00:11:41,742
all those
who feel left out.

169
00:11:41,743 --> 00:11:43,202
We get the youth vote.

170
00:11:43,203 --> 00:11:45,705
Now, all that rubs off on us
for the next election,

171
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:47,498
and in two months
he's replaced.

172
00:11:47,498 --> 00:11:50,542
Now you tell me, what
the hell's wrong with that?

173
00:11:52,420 --> 00:11:53,629
Makes a lot of sense,
Mr. Bailey.

174
00:11:53,630 --> 00:11:55,548
It's very clever.

175
00:11:55,548 --> 00:11:57,967
We can really use that to
create the image of the party

176
00:11:57,967 --> 00:12:01,804
that's bringing everybody
together.

177
00:12:01,804 --> 00:12:04,181
That's real middle-of-the-road
America stuff.

178
00:12:04,182 --> 00:12:05,850
And it fits in perfectly
with your campaign

179
00:12:05,850 --> 00:12:08,310
of Joe Payne,
man of the people.

180
00:12:08,311 --> 00:12:12,023
It's still a risk.

181
00:12:12,023 --> 00:12:13,941
Okay, all right.

182
00:12:13,942 --> 00:12:15,860
But don't let
that dumb cowboy--

183
00:12:15,860 --> 00:12:17,528
ah-ah! Indian.

184
00:12:17,528 --> 00:12:19,696
Cowboy, Indian, whatever!

185
00:12:19,697 --> 00:12:22,032
Don't let him
open an eye, an ear,

186
00:12:22,033 --> 00:12:25,619
or more important, his mouth.

187
00:12:29,999 --> 00:12:31,375
Billy Jack:
Ah, grandfather...

188
00:12:31,376 --> 00:12:33,127
What do we know of Washington,

189
00:12:33,127 --> 00:12:37,297
let alone the dirty world
of politics?

190
00:12:37,298 --> 00:12:41,510
Maybe that's why
you should go. As a test.

191
00:12:41,511 --> 00:12:45,473
Politics has
its own kind of violence.

192
00:12:45,473 --> 00:12:49,143
But how can I even think
of changing things out there

193
00:12:49,143 --> 00:12:52,062
when I have so much work to do
in changing myself, in here?

194
00:12:52,063 --> 00:12:54,857
If you want to become
a whole person,

195
00:12:54,857 --> 00:12:58,485
you must first try
to make society better.

196
00:12:58,486 --> 00:13:01,489
Before you have a right
to turn your back on it.

197
00:13:01,489 --> 00:13:03,699
I don't think that I could
do it away from here,

198
00:13:03,700 --> 00:13:05,535
though, grandfather.

199
00:13:05,535 --> 00:13:09,205
I mean, the canyon lady
is all my strength now.

200
00:13:09,205 --> 00:13:12,208
Then pray to her at sunrise.

201
00:13:12,208 --> 00:13:14,251
If you ask her spirits
to guide and purify you,

202
00:13:14,252 --> 00:13:18,381
dedicate your work to her,
and do the best you can,

203
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:22,881
then your work
will be your prayer,

204
00:13:23,177 --> 00:13:27,014
and the results need
not concern you.

205
00:14:57,355 --> 00:14:59,482
You know that classified
material senator foley

206
00:14:59,482 --> 00:15:02,902
was waving around before
he had his heart attack?

207
00:15:02,902 --> 00:15:05,404
I have it.

208
00:15:05,405 --> 00:15:09,325
A lot of people wondering
what happened to that stuff.

209
00:15:09,325 --> 00:15:11,452
I can leak it,
or I can trade it.

210
00:15:14,872 --> 00:15:17,666
Well, what do you have in mind?

211
00:15:17,667 --> 00:15:22,167
A white house level appointment,
and a salary of say, $48,000.

212
00:15:24,132 --> 00:15:26,759
You play dangerous games, Dan.

213
00:15:26,759 --> 00:15:29,553
Gary, I'm not playing games.

214
00:15:29,554 --> 00:15:31,472
You get back to me
within 72 hours,

215
00:15:31,472 --> 00:15:33,640
or I'll have to leak
this thing to the post.

216
00:15:33,641 --> 00:15:36,060
Or maybe I'll give it to some
crusading young senator

217
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:39,438
who needs the publicity.

218
00:15:39,439 --> 00:15:41,357
Well, all I can do
is make a report.

219
00:15:49,157 --> 00:15:51,617
And in that spirit, we have
gathered here tonight to

220
00:15:51,617 --> 00:15:56,117
acclaim and to bid godspeed to
the newest, and maybe in time,

221
00:15:56,706 --> 00:16:01,206
the best senator our state
has ever seen, Billy Jack.

222
00:16:09,552 --> 00:16:13,305
Thank you, governor,
and, ladies and gentlemen,

223
00:16:13,306 --> 00:16:15,433
I don't think we need
two men in Washington

224
00:16:15,433 --> 00:16:19,353
when we have a senator like
Joseph Payne representing us.

225
00:16:23,024 --> 00:16:25,067
He probably
doesn't remember me,

226
00:16:25,067 --> 00:16:29,567
but you see, ah, he knew
my uncle very well.

227
00:16:29,947 --> 00:16:32,115
William trotter was the name

228
00:16:32,116 --> 00:16:34,493
they put on him
in the Christian school.

229
00:16:34,494 --> 00:16:37,997
Man of the bear
was his Indian name.

230
00:16:37,997 --> 00:16:40,666
Well, senator Payne
and my uncle worked together

231
00:16:40,666 --> 00:16:41,833
on the restoration
of that Indian land

232
00:16:41,834 --> 00:16:44,503
up around green lake
years ago,

233
00:16:44,504 --> 00:16:49,004
and well, ah, I remember that my
uncle told me that Joseph Payne

234
00:16:50,426 --> 00:16:54,596
was the finest man
that he had ever known.

235
00:17:08,277 --> 00:17:11,238
Billy, you're so much
like your uncle.

236
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:15,367
Oh, well, thank you.

237
00:17:15,368 --> 00:17:18,496
When I look at you, I can
almost see him sitting behind

238
00:17:18,496 --> 00:17:22,791
that roll top desk, with his hat
on, getting out his newspaper.

239
00:17:22,792 --> 00:17:24,752
He said he always
kept the hat on

240
00:17:24,752 --> 00:17:27,254
so he'd be ready to do battle.

241
00:17:27,255 --> 00:17:29,173
William trotter--
man of the bear--

242
00:17:29,173 --> 00:17:32,885
editor, publisher, and
champion of lost causes.

243
00:17:32,885 --> 00:17:35,304
Yeah, he always said the only
causes worth fighting for

244
00:17:35,304 --> 00:17:36,888
were the lost causes.

245
00:17:36,889 --> 00:17:38,473
You don't need to tell me.

246
00:17:38,474 --> 00:17:40,934
We were a team, the two of us.

247
00:17:40,935 --> 00:17:42,937
Struggling Indian
out of journalism school,

248
00:17:42,937 --> 00:17:45,189
struggling lawyer-

249
00:17:45,189 --> 00:17:47,691
they used to call us the twin
champions of lost causes,

250
00:17:47,692 --> 00:17:50,569
and we took on plenty.

251
00:17:50,570 --> 00:17:54,615
You might call us the first of
the store-front law centers.

252
00:17:54,615 --> 00:17:55,866
We didn't have much to eat,

253
00:17:55,866 --> 00:17:58,618
but we sure had
plenty of lost causes.

254
00:17:58,619 --> 00:18:00,329
It was before your time.

255
00:18:00,329 --> 00:18:03,999
Yeah, but our people
still talk of those battles.

256
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:07,128
His last fight
was his best, Billy.

257
00:18:07,128 --> 00:18:10,339
He and that four page newspaper
against the mining syndicate

258
00:18:10,339 --> 00:18:13,967
that had come to strip mine the
land, just like that black mesa.

259
00:18:13,968 --> 00:18:15,803
Steal the reservations,
pollute the air,

260
00:18:15,803 --> 00:18:17,346
and rape the sacred hill.

261
00:18:17,346 --> 00:18:21,266
Ah, they tried everything--
bribery, intimidation.

262
00:18:22,727 --> 00:18:23,769
And then.

263
00:18:23,769 --> 00:18:25,103
What happened?

264
00:18:25,104 --> 00:18:28,482
They found him slumped over
his desk one morning.

265
00:18:28,482 --> 00:18:32,402
Shot in the back.

266
00:18:32,403 --> 00:18:36,115
When I got there,
i could still see him

267
00:18:36,115 --> 00:18:38,450
sitting at that roll top desk.

268
00:18:40,620 --> 00:18:41,704
Still with his hat on.

269
00:18:44,290 --> 00:18:46,166
Still with his hat on.

270
00:18:50,463 --> 00:18:53,757
Come in

271
00:18:53,758 --> 00:18:54,884
am I interrupting?

272
00:18:54,884 --> 00:18:57,219
Oh, come in, Saunders.

273
00:18:57,219 --> 00:19:00,305
Sit down, sit down.

274
00:19:00,306 --> 00:19:03,475
Now, what's all this about
you're wanting to quit?

275
00:19:03,476 --> 00:19:04,935
Look, senator,
i wasn't given a brain

276
00:19:04,935 --> 00:19:08,480
just to tell some nature boy
what time it is.

277
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:09,982
I'm not a registered nurse.

278
00:19:09,982 --> 00:19:12,275
Sam foley couldn't
get along without you,

279
00:19:12,276 --> 00:19:14,569
and neither can i
at the moment.

280
00:19:14,570 --> 00:19:15,654
Five minutes, senator.

281
00:19:15,655 --> 00:19:17,114
You've got to get
to the floor.

282
00:19:17,114 --> 00:19:18,365
I'll be right there,

283
00:19:18,366 --> 00:19:20,034
and get that foreign relations
material ready, will you?

284
00:19:20,034 --> 00:19:22,953
It's right there at your
fingertips, all of it.

285
00:19:22,953 --> 00:19:25,372
Now look, Saunders, I haven't
got time to go into all this,

286
00:19:25,373 --> 00:19:27,333
but foley told me wild horses

287
00:19:27,333 --> 00:19:31,628
couldn't pull confidential
material out of you.

288
00:19:31,629 --> 00:19:35,049
I'm an old hand at following
instructions, senator.

289
00:19:35,049 --> 00:19:39,549
I need someone who can be
trusted to occupy Billy Jack

290
00:19:39,804 --> 00:19:40,971
and keep him out of trouble.

291
00:19:40,971 --> 00:19:43,348
Oh, but, senator,
i just, I won't do that.

292
00:19:43,349 --> 00:19:46,143
But, Saunders, you too smart
a girl to do anything foolish.

293
00:19:46,143 --> 00:19:49,437
Now if certain things
happen to me,

294
00:19:49,438 --> 00:19:53,024
I'm taking everybody
up with me.

295
00:19:53,025 --> 00:19:54,693
Sir, when I first got
to this city,

296
00:19:54,694 --> 00:19:57,655
my eyes were big
green question marks.

297
00:19:57,655 --> 00:20:01,033
Now they're big green
dollar marks.

298
00:20:01,033 --> 00:20:02,117
All right.

299
00:20:02,118 --> 00:20:03,828
You finish this job properly,

300
00:20:03,828 --> 00:20:07,164
keep him away from anything
that smells of politics,

301
00:20:07,164 --> 00:20:10,083
and not only will you receive
a very handsome bonus,

302
00:20:10,084 --> 00:20:13,420
but one of the best jobs
in Washington.

303
00:20:13,421 --> 00:20:14,713
Thank you, sir.

304
00:20:14,714 --> 00:20:18,884
Thank you very much, senator.

305
00:20:18,884 --> 00:20:20,343
Oh, senator,
does the smell of politics

306
00:20:20,344 --> 00:20:24,844
include the willet creek
nuclear reactor?

307
00:20:28,352 --> 00:20:31,146
If you're speaking
of the deficiency bill,

308
00:20:31,147 --> 00:20:32,565
especially that.

309
00:20:44,869 --> 00:20:46,370
Senator, good morning.

310
00:20:46,370 --> 00:20:47,662
We were a little curious

311
00:20:47,663 --> 00:20:50,332
how you'd be voting
on the energy bill.

312
00:20:50,332 --> 00:20:53,543
Oh, ah, I'll be voting no
on the energy bill.

313
00:20:53,544 --> 00:20:58,044
I see. Ls this the way senator
Payne advised you to vote?

314
00:20:58,174 --> 00:21:01,343
Senator Payne is also voting no,
is that what you mean?

315
00:21:01,343 --> 00:21:04,596
Yes, thank you.

316
00:21:04,597 --> 00:21:07,349
To my mind, I can think
of nothing more pressing,

317
00:21:07,349 --> 00:21:09,017
in view of the depletion
of our resources

318
00:21:09,018 --> 00:21:11,729
and the advanced inadequacy
of our technology

319
00:21:11,729 --> 00:21:16,229
to magically solve our problems
as we have supposed.

320
00:21:16,859 --> 00:21:18,861
And in view of the imminent
possibility

321
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:21,864
of our running out
of energy of all kinds,

322
00:21:21,864 --> 00:21:23,365
I urge immediate passage

323
00:21:23,365 --> 00:21:25,492
of the gentleman
from Colorado's bill.

324
00:21:32,708 --> 00:21:35,669
Pardon me, senator,
but either I'm hearing things,

325
00:21:35,669 --> 00:21:37,587
or I actually heard you

326
00:21:37,588 --> 00:21:39,464
just urging passage
of the energy bill.

327
00:21:39,465 --> 00:21:41,383
That's right.

328
00:21:41,383 --> 00:21:43,593
Well, sir, I just told
the press outside

329
00:21:43,594 --> 00:21:45,262
that both of us
were voting no.

330
00:21:45,262 --> 00:21:47,347
I am voting no.

331
00:21:47,348 --> 00:21:49,641
I'm sorry.
Now I don't understand.

332
00:21:49,642 --> 00:21:52,394
You see,
half the people back home

333
00:21:52,394 --> 00:21:54,729
wanted a speech urging
passage of the bill,

334
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:56,648
and the other half
wanted us to vote no.

335
00:21:56,649 --> 00:21:59,193
This way, everybody's happy.

336
00:21:59,193 --> 00:22:01,945
In order to get the vital
issues taken care of,

337
00:22:01,946 --> 00:22:04,156
you've got to
sugar coat the rest

338
00:22:04,156 --> 00:22:06,158
so there's a little
something for everybody.

339
00:22:06,158 --> 00:22:07,826
But, sir,
this is a vital issue.

340
00:22:07,827 --> 00:22:10,120
Exactly.
It's much too sensitive

341
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:12,122
to ever come up for a vote.

342
00:22:12,122 --> 00:22:13,581
It will be referred
back to committee

343
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:15,750
where it'll be buried.

344
00:22:15,751 --> 00:22:17,252
You'll get used to it.

345
00:22:17,253 --> 00:22:19,838
Ah, Joe, I'd like
to work out a little trade

346
00:22:19,839 --> 00:22:22,216
on my cotton subsidy bill.

347
00:22:22,216 --> 00:22:24,259
Frankly, senator,
i think I made a mistake

348
00:22:24,260 --> 00:22:25,636
when I accepted
this appointment.

349
00:22:25,636 --> 00:22:27,638
No, wait a minute.

350
00:22:27,638 --> 00:22:30,766
Didn't you say something about
a national children's camp?

351
00:22:30,766 --> 00:22:32,768
Now, I assume you were
in earnest about that?

352
00:22:32,768 --> 00:22:34,352
Well, yes, very much so.

353
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:35,520
Well, there.

354
00:22:35,521 --> 00:22:38,023
I've got a job for both of you.

355
00:22:38,023 --> 00:22:40,150
Why don't you
put a bill together

356
00:22:40,150 --> 00:22:42,193
to accomplish that and
present it to congress?

357
00:22:42,194 --> 00:22:44,362
Now, that'd be a great
experience for Billy,

358
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:46,823
and for you
as a legislative aide.

359
00:22:46,824 --> 00:22:48,534
You know, if we could do just

360
00:22:48,534 --> 00:22:50,369
that one thing
while we're here--

361
00:22:50,369 --> 00:22:52,204
I mean, if we could
make that children's camp

362
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:53,371
become a reality.

363
00:22:53,372 --> 00:22:54,456
Well, what's to stop you?

364
00:22:54,456 --> 00:22:56,082
Saunders
will help you with it.

365
00:22:56,083 --> 00:22:57,918
There isn't anyone on the hill

366
00:22:57,918 --> 00:22:59,711
smarter than Saunders
about senate procedure.

367
00:23:01,297 --> 00:23:04,508
You know, this whole business
of politics is a kind of art--

368
00:23:04,508 --> 00:23:06,092
a hand-me-down
from one generation

369
00:23:06,093 --> 00:23:08,053
to the next art at that.

370
00:23:23,402 --> 00:23:25,821
Guard:
Guards, halt.

371
00:23:33,787 --> 00:23:35,455
Well?

372
00:23:35,456 --> 00:23:37,583
It's all been arranged.

373
00:23:37,583 --> 00:23:40,752
White house
or state department?

374
00:23:40,753 --> 00:23:45,215
Junior executive level for six
months, then it's up to you.

375
00:23:45,215 --> 00:23:47,634
When will the appointment come?

376
00:23:47,635 --> 00:23:49,345
30 days after delivery.

377
00:23:50,888 --> 00:23:54,057
How will they know the delivery
is all that you have?

378
00:23:54,058 --> 00:23:55,809
You wouldn't hold back any
hidden copies from me,

379
00:23:55,809 --> 00:23:56,643
would you, Dan?

380
00:23:56,644 --> 00:23:58,270
Hey! Come on.

381
00:23:59,730 --> 00:24:01,356
How long have we
known each other?

382
00:24:04,485 --> 00:24:07,154
You have my word.

383
00:24:07,154 --> 00:24:09,906
What do you mean,
the head man's writing a bill?

384
00:24:09,907 --> 00:24:11,909
He's a senator, isn't he?

385
00:24:11,909 --> 00:24:13,243
Wants to work all night.

386
00:24:13,243 --> 00:24:15,828
Honey, you know foley's
classified files?

387
00:24:15,829 --> 00:24:18,081
Does anyone besides me
know you've got that?

388
00:24:18,082 --> 00:24:21,001
Hey, honey, not now.

389
00:24:21,001 --> 00:24:23,920
We'll talk about it
later, okay?

390
00:24:23,921 --> 00:24:25,130
Don't work too hard.

391
00:24:25,130 --> 00:24:26,422
And have a good time.

392
00:24:36,433 --> 00:24:37,934
You have any idea
what it takes

393
00:24:37,935 --> 00:24:39,603
to get a bill passed
through congress?

394
00:24:39,603 --> 00:24:41,813
I haven't the vaguest idea

395
00:24:41,814 --> 00:24:43,148
what it takes to
get a bill passed,

396
00:24:43,148 --> 00:24:45,358
but Payne said
you're an expert.

397
00:24:45,359 --> 00:24:46,943
Just tell us,
what do we have to do?

398
00:24:46,944 --> 00:24:51,031
Let's pretend its tomorrow
and your bill is ready.

399
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:53,450
You just take it on over
to the honorable senate

400
00:24:53,450 --> 00:24:54,451
and you introduce it.

401
00:24:54,451 --> 00:24:55,577
How?

402
00:24:55,577 --> 00:24:57,203
You get to your feet
and take a deep breath,

403
00:24:57,204 --> 00:24:58,538
and you start spouting.

404
00:24:58,539 --> 00:25:01,542
Then a curly-haired page
will take it down to a desk

405
00:25:01,542 --> 00:25:03,126
where a long-faced clerk
will read it

406
00:25:03,127 --> 00:25:05,129
and refer it
to the right committee.

407
00:25:05,129 --> 00:25:06,296
Why a committee?

408
00:25:06,296 --> 00:25:07,630
Because that's how congress

409
00:25:07,631 --> 00:25:09,507
or any other large body
has to be run.

410
00:25:09,508 --> 00:25:11,051
All your work has to be
done through committees.

411
00:25:11,051 --> 00:25:12,052
Yeah, but why?

412
00:25:12,052 --> 00:25:13,178
You can't just take a bill

413
00:25:13,178 --> 00:25:14,470
no one's
ever heard of before

414
00:25:14,471 --> 00:25:16,514
and discuss it
among 100 men,

415
00:25:16,515 --> 00:25:18,391
most of whom
aren't there anyway

416
00:25:18,392 --> 00:25:21,311
because they're off
on campaigns or committees.

417
00:25:21,311 --> 00:25:22,812
Anyway, where are we?

418
00:25:22,813 --> 00:25:24,564
- We're in committee.
- In committee, right.

419
00:25:24,565 --> 00:25:27,150
All right, well they hand it
down to a sub-committee.

420
00:25:27,151 --> 00:25:29,236
And then they really
give it a going over.

421
00:25:29,236 --> 00:25:32,239
They hold hearings, they call
in people, they ask questions.

422
00:25:32,239 --> 00:25:35,659
Now, days are going by,
senator. Days, weeks maybe.

423
00:25:35,659 --> 00:25:37,077
All right, say finally
after all that,

424
00:25:37,077 --> 00:25:38,703
they think it's quite a bill.

425
00:25:38,704 --> 00:25:40,914
It goes on over to
the house of representatives

426
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:42,415
for a debate and a vote.

427
00:25:42,416 --> 00:25:44,668
Only it has to wait
its turn on the calendar.

428
00:25:44,668 --> 00:25:46,419
A calendar?

429
00:25:46,420 --> 00:25:48,839
Calendar. You know,
the order of business.

430
00:25:48,839 --> 00:25:51,716
Anyway, your bill has to wait
way back there in line,

431
00:25:51,717 --> 00:25:53,385
unless you know somebody
on a steering committee

432
00:25:53,385 --> 00:25:54,511
and you can
get them to think--

433
00:25:54,511 --> 00:25:55,929
- what is that?
- What?

434
00:25:55,929 --> 00:25:57,597
A steering committee.

435
00:25:57,598 --> 00:25:59,516
It's a committee
of majority party leaders,

436
00:25:59,516 --> 00:26:02,185
and they decide whether
a bill is important enough

437
00:26:02,186 --> 00:26:04,354
to be moved up
to the head of the list.

438
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:06,064
I betcha we could
get Payne to help.

439
00:26:06,065 --> 00:26:07,232
Oh, yeah.

440
00:26:07,232 --> 00:26:09,192
Oh, yeah, he'll be a big help.

441
00:26:09,193 --> 00:26:10,861
Oh, okay, where are we?

442
00:26:10,861 --> 00:26:12,445
We're in the house.

443
00:26:12,446 --> 00:26:15,949
Ah, house makes more changes,
and more amendments,

444
00:26:15,949 --> 00:26:17,867
and they send it
back over to the senate.

445
00:26:17,868 --> 00:26:20,120
The senate doesn't like what
the house did to the bill,

446
00:26:20,120 --> 00:26:21,871
so they make more changes.

447
00:26:21,872 --> 00:26:25,458
And then the house doesn't like
those changes, so it's stymied.

448
00:26:25,459 --> 00:26:29,546
So they have to call in
a man from both houses,

449
00:26:29,546 --> 00:26:31,756
and they go into a huddle,
called a conference,

450
00:26:31,757 --> 00:26:33,133
and they battle it out.

451
00:26:33,133 --> 00:26:36,469
Now, in the meantime,
all the lobbyists interested

452
00:26:36,470 --> 00:26:38,972
are holding cocktail parties
for and against the bill,

453
00:26:38,972 --> 00:26:43,472
and unmarked envelopes are being
generously supplied with cash

454
00:26:44,436 --> 00:26:46,646
and passed out
to all the swing votes.

455
00:26:46,647 --> 00:26:48,982
Anyway, after all this
vivisection,

456
00:26:48,982 --> 00:26:51,317
it begins to be traded.

457
00:26:51,318 --> 00:26:53,320
That means that somebody
can trade off a portion

458
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:54,404
in their bill

459
00:26:54,404 --> 00:26:56,739
if you'll trade off
a portion in your bill

460
00:26:56,740 --> 00:26:58,992
and make everybody happy.

461
00:26:58,992 --> 00:27:02,912
And after all this, the bill
finally comes to a vote.

462
00:27:02,913 --> 00:27:07,413
Oh, yeah, the big day finally
comes, and congress adjourns.

463
00:27:08,961 --> 00:27:10,504
You catching on, senator?

464
00:27:10,504 --> 00:27:12,088
Sort of.

465
00:27:14,800 --> 00:27:15,759
Well...

466
00:27:17,928 --> 00:27:19,262
When do we start?

467
00:27:19,263 --> 00:27:20,764
What?

468
00:27:23,183 --> 00:27:24,851
Senator, do you think
we could get on

469
00:27:24,852 --> 00:27:26,436
with the particulars now?

470
00:27:26,436 --> 00:27:27,979
Four hundred acres, you say?

471
00:27:27,980 --> 00:27:29,481
Where's it gonna be located?

472
00:27:29,481 --> 00:27:32,775
Situated in ambrose county,
kerry canyon,

473
00:27:32,776 --> 00:27:34,778
right at the fork
on the river,

474
00:27:34,778 --> 00:27:37,864
about a mile and half
upstream on willett creek.

475
00:27:37,865 --> 00:27:40,158
- Where?
- Willett creek.

476
00:27:40,159 --> 00:27:42,703
It's just where the stream
rolls down into the river.

477
00:27:42,703 --> 00:27:43,870
In kerry canyon?

478
00:27:43,871 --> 00:27:45,122
Yeah, why?
Do you know about it?

479
00:27:45,122 --> 00:27:46,039
Have you ever been out there?

480
00:27:46,039 --> 00:27:48,499
No, no, I haven't.

481
00:27:48,500 --> 00:27:51,711
Have you discussed this exact
location with senator Payne?

482
00:27:51,712 --> 00:27:54,506
No, not the exact location.

483
00:27:54,506 --> 00:27:56,049
Why?

484
00:27:56,049 --> 00:27:58,843
No reason. No reason.

485
00:27:58,844 --> 00:28:02,347
Four hundred acres,
either side of willett creek.

486
00:28:02,347 --> 00:28:05,558
So, dragging me up
to the hill at this hour,

487
00:28:05,559 --> 00:28:07,060
this really better be good.

488
00:28:07,060 --> 00:28:08,728
I don't know
if it's gonna be good,

489
00:28:08,729 --> 00:28:10,355
but it's certainly
gonna be interesting.

490
00:28:10,355 --> 00:28:12,231
You know, for a guy who's
supposed to have been so brave,

491
00:28:12,232 --> 00:28:13,566
I've never seen anybody
more nervous

492
00:28:13,567 --> 00:28:15,402
about getting up
and reading a bill.

493
00:28:15,402 --> 00:28:16,569
By the way, honey,

494
00:28:16,570 --> 00:28:18,405
do you know where the keys
to the safe deposit box are?

495
00:28:18,405 --> 00:28:20,156
Yeah, but why?
Don't you?

496
00:28:20,157 --> 00:28:21,324
Oh, sure.

497
00:28:21,325 --> 00:28:22,659
What'd ya ask for?

498
